detailedRequirements:
Task Overview

In 2013, over a dozen large asteroids similar in size to the space stone that crashed into Russia in February 2013 passed near Earth. Near-Earth Object (“NEO”) detection and characterization is a critical need for NASA and the United States. NASA has been directed to develop capabilities to observe, track and characterized NEOs and other deep space objects that could pose a threat to the Earth.  As a result, NASA is developing concepts for a highly capable deep space radar array consisting of sets of commercially available monolithic antennas.

NEOs are observable with commercial radar technology. Specifically, asteroids can be tracked with Ka-band radar. NASA’s Ka-Band Object Observation and Monitoring (“KaBOOM”) project plans to use commercial 12 meter Ka-band radar dishes to build large dish arrays capable of simultaneously tracking many objects at safe distances. This raises the possibility that the detection range for Earth-bound asteroids can be inexpensively extended and maintained. 

One of the challenges faced by NASA is determining the optimum selection of individual antennas within the array for a given track observation.  This is a complex analysis and goes directly to development of the concept of operations and cost of operations (in terms of maintenance and total capacity required).

KaBOOM project will feature a series of challenges that task competitors to develop a flexible model that can be used to determine both the optimum selection of existing dishes to track a set of objects, and the optimum placement of any number of new dishes added to an existing array.

Refer to the KaBOOM official minisite for more information http://www.topcoder.com/asteroids/tracker/

The first challenge is a Marathon Match (MM) to solve the optimization/multi-track dish selection problem. To focus MM competitors attention on this difficult task, we built a base-line reference beam model that will be used in the evaluation and scoring of competitors solutions. The MM challenge also requires an offline tester / visualizer to allow contestants to monitor the performance of their work. The goal of this challenge is to implement the graphics for the MM offline tester / visualizer tool. 

Task Requirements

The task of this challenge is to develop source code for the graphics part of a Java GUI that implements the interface given below. Your class will be initialized with some information that will be constant throughout the simulation. Your class will then be called repeatedly for each time step in the simulation, giving the status and information for the current time step. The purpose of the class is to visualize this information.

The information to visualize that is constant throughout the simulation is the following: 

  • A background hemisphere seen from above with some longitude lines/latitude circles
  • Radar positions in 2D
The information to visualize that is changing each time step is the following:
  • Asteroid positions in 2D
  • Which asteroid each radar is targeting (or radar is turned off), this can be visualized by drawing a line between the radar and asteroid

For each time step, there is also two numerical values associated with each radar and asteroid. For the radars, they are the following:

  • Current wall power for this radar
  • Current noise for this radar, induced from the other radars

For the asteroids, they are the following:

  • Current signal power reflected from the asteroid
  • Current knowledge score for the asteroid
The numerical values for each radar and asteroid should be printed besides them.

Also, for each time step, there is some global numerical values that should be printed. These are:

  • Simulation time in seconds, should be printed in standard time format (xx:xx:xx). Simulation is less than 24h.
  • Current consumed energy in kilowatt hour
  • Current total score

These values should be printed to the right of the hemisphere in a separate section. 

A previous "proof of concept" of this visualizer was written in C++. A snapshot of this old visualizer can be seen below. Use a standard gray background instead of black, and print the time, score, etc, in a separate section to the right. Also note thay you need to print numerical values alongside the radars and asteroids, which is not shown in the picture.

All positions are given in normalized coordinates, this means they are between 0.0 and 1.0. The GUI you develop should be resizable and render these coordinates appropriately.

Your class is given a KeyListener and a WindowListener in the initialize function. They should be added to receive events from the GUI.

 
Interface
You should implement the following interface:
/*  * This is the interface for the graphics part for the marathon visualizer  */ 
interface Drawer { 
/*      
 * Provide all information about the radars and the asteroids in this testcase      
 */ 
  public void initialize(int hemisphereRadius,  // initial radius of the hemisphere in pixels, but the window should be resizable 
    KeyListener keyListener,   // key listener for this GUI 
    WindowListener windowListener,  // window listener for this GUI
    List<Double> latitudeCircles,  // list of normalized radius (between [0, 1]) for the latitude circles 
    List<Double> longitudeLines,   // list of angels in radians for the longitude lines  
    List<Point2D.Double> radarPositions);  // list of normalized radar positions (x and y between [0, 1]) 
/*
 * Called each timestep. Updates the information that should be visualized.      
 */ 
public void update(int time, // current simulation time in seconds 
      double score,   // current score  
      double energyUsed,   // current energy used 
      List<Point2D.Double> asteroidPositions,  // current list of normalized asteroid positions, (0.0, 0.0) means it's not visible 
      List<Double> asteroidKnowledgeScore,  // current knowledge score for each asteroid (same length as asteroidPositions) 
      List<Double> asteroidSignalPower,  // current signal power for each asteroid (same length as asteroidPositions) 
      List<Double> radarWallPower ,    // current wall power for each radar (same length as radarPositions in initialize)
      List<Double> radarNoisePower,     // current noise power for each radar (same length as radarPositions in initialize) 
      List<RadarAssignment> radarAssignments);     // current power and assigned asteroid (or -1 if unassigned) for each radar 
} 

class RadarAssignment { // Default constructor: radar is off 
public RadarAssignment() { 
  this.power = 0.0; 
  this.asteroidIndex = -1; 
} 

public double power; // current power for radar, 0.0 means the radar is turned off 
public int asteroidIndex; // which asteroid to synchronize on, or -1 if radar should be turned off 
}

finalSubmissionGuidelines:
Submission Deliverables

Below is an overview of the deliverables:

  • Source code for a Java GUI that implements the given interface and visualizes the information as described.
  • A complete and detailed deployment document explaining how to deploy and run the visualizer.

Final Submission

For each member, the final submission should be uploaded to the Online Review Tool.
